      <!-- FAQ Section -->
      <div id="faq" class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 shadow-sm p-8 mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] text-[#1B3A5C] mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <div class="space-y-4">
          <details class="group border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
            <summary class="cursor-pointer p-4 font-semibold font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] text-[#1B3A5C] flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-gray-50 transition-colors">
              <span>How often should an industrial disc centrifuge be serviced?</span>
              <span class="group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform text-[#E8A317]">&#9660;</span>
            </summary>
            <div class="px-4 pb-4 font-['Source_Sans_3'] text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
              <p class="mb-2">Minor bowl service intervals range from 2-3 weeks (for aggressive chemicals or abrasive solids) to 3-6 months (for benign fluids like lubricating oil). The specific centrifuge application and the condition of the process fluid determine the exact interval.</p>
              <p>Industrial centrifuge manufacturers recommend a major overhaul of the disc centrifuge every 2-3 years, based on the expected lifespan of transmission components and bowl wear. We recommend frequent inspection during the initial startup phase to establish the ideal service schedule for your specific operating conditions.</p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="group border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
            <summary class="cursor-pointer p-4 font-semibold font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] text-[#1B3A5C] flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-gray-50 transition-colors">
              <span>How much does it cost to repair an industrial centrifuge?</span>
              <span class="group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform text-[#E8A317]">&#9660;</span>
            </summary>
            <div class="px-4 pb-4 font-['Source_Sans_3'] text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
              <p class="mb-2">Repair costs vary by centrifuge type and service level. Minor service starts at $800+ for small manual-clean disc centrifuges and $2,500+ for medium self-cleaning models. Major service ranges from $2,000+ to $13,000+ depending on the centrifuge size and type.</p>
              <p>Complete rebuilds cost $5,000+ for small disc centrifuges up to $18,000+ for medium decanter centrifuges. These costs include all replacement parts, labor, testing, and quality assurance. Contact Dolphin Centrifuge for a detailed quote specific to your centrifuge model and condition.</p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="group border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
            <summary class="cursor-pointer p-4 font-semibold font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] text-[#1B3A5C] flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-gray-50 transition-colors">
              <span>How long does a centrifuge rebuild take?</span>
              <span class="group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform text-[#E8A317]">&#9660;</span>
            </summary>
            <div class="px-4 pb-4 font-['Source_Sans_3'] text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
              <p>Rebuild turnaround time depends on centrifuge size and repair scope. A small disc centrifuge can be rebuilt in about three days, whereas a large capacity self-cleaning disc centrifuge can take four weeks or more for a complete overhaul. The availability of replacement parts and the extent of wear damage also affect the timeline. Dolphin Centrifuge maintains an extensive parts inventory to minimize delays.</p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="group border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
            <summary class="cursor-pointer p-4 font-semibold font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] text-[#1B3A5C] flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-gray-50 transition-colors">
              <span>What is included in a complete centrifuge rebuild?</span>
              <span class="group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform text-[#E8A317]">&#9660;</span>
            </summary>
            <div class="px-4 pb-4 font-['Source_Sans_3'] text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
              <p class="mb-2">A complete centrifuge rebuild includes stripping the machine down to bare metal, cleaning all bowl and transmission parts, sandblasting and painting the frame with durable epoxy topcoat, inspecting and testing all critical parts for dimensional tolerance, and replacing worn parts with new or rebuilt components.</p>
              <p>All bearings are replaced with OEM-recommended high-speed bearings, and all consumable parts including O-Rings, Gaskets, Friction Material, and Belts are replaced. The centrifuge is then rebuilt to original specifications and undergoes comprehensive mechanical and operational testing before delivery.</p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="group border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
            <summary class="cursor-pointer p-4 font-semibold font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] text-[#1B3A5C] flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-gray-50 transition-colors">
              <span>What service kits should centrifuge operators keep in stock?</span>
              <span class="group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform text-[#E8A317]">&#9660;</span>
            </summary>
            <div class="px-4 pb-4 font-['Source_Sans_3'] text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
              <p class="mb-2">Centrifuge operators should keep bowl service kits (containing O-rings, seals, and gaskets) in stock at all times. These kits are inexpensive and easy to store, and having them on hand significantly reduces service downtime.</p>
              <p>Additional recommended stock includes bowl outlet gaskets, centrifuge-specific seal lubricant, operating water nozzles (which are wear items), friction pads for friction clutch models, and drive belts for belt-drive models. Periodic centrifuge maintenance using these kits prevents unplanned downtime and the significant production losses that come with it.</p>
            </div>
          </details>
        </div>
      </div>

